{"type":"message","id":"a1b938c3","parentId":"74d6d42c","timestamp":"2026-02-15T18:56:11.735Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[Sun 2026-02-15 20:56 GMT+2] OPERATION: DOMAIN ISOLATION PROTOCOL UPDATE.\n\n1.  **Protocol Update (`MASTER_PROTOCOL.md`):**\n    *   *Add Section:* \"Section 12: Domain Management (System vs App)\".\n    *   *Define:*\n        *   **SYSTEM DOMAIN:** `openclaw.json`, `MASTER_PROTOCOL.md`, `ACTIVE_CONTEXT.json`, `specs/PRD_TEMPLATE.md`, `skills/`.\n        *   **APP DOMAIN:** `src/`, `tests/`, `requirements.txt`, `Dockerfile`, `docker-compose.yml`.\n    *   *Gatekeeper Rule:* \"Classify intent before action. Never mix domains in one commit.\"\n    *   *Triggers:* \"System Upgrade\" vs \"Bot Update\".\n\n2.  **Sacred Core List:**\n    *   Generate a list of files that are strictly System Domain.\n\n3.  **Output:**\n    *   Confirmation of Protocol write.\n    *   Sacred Core file list.\n    *   Ready for \"System Upgrade\" or \"Bot Update\"."}],"timestamp":1771181771733}}
{"type":"message","id":"25df16cc","parentId":"a1b938c3","timestamp":"2026-02-15T18:56:23.233Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Analyzing the Protocol Update**\n\nI'm focused on the \"Domain Isolation Protocol Update,\" as requested. The core of this lies in defining domain boundaries. I've been wrestling with the best way to structure \"Section 12: Domain Management\" in `MASTER_PROTOCOL.md`. It seems the System vs. App domain differentiation requires very clear, actionable rules, a challenge that I am currently considering. I will now create the \"Sacred Core\" files list.\n\n\n**Considering File Existence Check**\n\nI'm now shifting my focus to the foundational step: verifying the existence of `MASTER_PROTOCOL.md`. I'm devising a robust method to determine its presence before proceeding. It's crucial to handle potential scenarios where the file might be missing or inaccessible. A smooth and automated check is paramount before Section 12 can be drafted, and the file list can be created.\n\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"read_1771181783227_206","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"MASTER_PROTOCOL.md"},"thoughtSignature":""}],"api":"google-vertex","provider":"google-vertex","model":"gemini-3-pro-preview","usage":{"input":4586,"output":116,"cacheRead":2192,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":4702,"cost":{"input":0.009172,"output":0.001392,"cacheRead":0.00043840000000000003,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0110024}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1771181771734}}
{"type":"message","id":"08d145cc","parentId":"25df16cc","timestamp":"2026-02-15T18:56:23.259Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"read_1771181783227_206","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# MASTER PROTOCOL (SACS-2026)\n\n**Version:** 3.0.0\n**Status:** ACTIVE\n**Enforcement:** MANDATORY\n\n---\n\n## 1. Core Philosophy (SACS-2026)\n\nThe System Architecture for Cognitive Synthesis (SACS-2026) governs all operations. We prioritize precision, speed, and safety above all else.\n\n*   **Autonomy with Oversight:** Agents operate autonomously but must report status and errors transparently.\n*   **Zero Ambiguity:** Specs must be written before code. Documentation is not an afterthought; it is the blueprint.\n*   **Speed is Safety:** In high-frequency environments, latency causes drift. Minimize latency to maintain control.\n*   **Self-Correction:** The system must identify, contain, and correct faults without human intervention whenever possible.\n\n## 2. Architecture\n\nWe employ a **Polyglot Hybrid Architecture** designed for maximum throughput and safety.\n\n### 2.1 Polyglot Stack\n*   **Rust (Core):** Used for high-performance compute, safety-critical logic, and memory management via PyO3 bindings.\n*   **Python (Glue):** Orchestrates high-level logic, agentic reasoning, and API integrations.\n*   **Shell (Ops):** Standard interface for system interactions.\n\n### 2.2 Memory & Communication\n*   **SharedMemory (HFT 3.0):** Used for the hot path (<0.01ms latency). Zero-copy IPC replaces Redis for critical signaling.\n*   **Redis Stack:** Used for **Agentic Memory** (vectorized logs, semantic search) and state persistence (cold/warm path).\n*   **Orjson:** Mandatory JSON serializer for microsecond-level parsing.\n\n### 2.3 Fleet Status\n*   **Active Nodes:** 730, 570\n*   **Configuration:** Centralized via `docs/ACTIVE_CONTEXT.json`.\n\n## 3. Safety Protocols\n\n### 3.1 The OODA Loop\nEvery task MUST follow the **Observe-Orient-Decide-Act** cycle.\n1.  **Observe:** Gather raw data (logs, state, user input).\n2.  **Orient:** Analyze context against SACS-2026 rules.\n3.  **Decide:** Formulate a plan (write spec/docs).\n4.  **Act:** Execute the change (atomic commit).\n\n### 3.2 Terminal Watchdog\n*   **Strict Oversight:** Agents must actively read `stdout` and `stderr`.\n*   **Zero Ignorance:** Never assume a command succeeded. Verify exit codes and output streams.\n*   **Halt on Error:** If a critical error is detected in `stderr`, the agent must pause and enter a recovery state.\n\n### 3.3 Atomic Rollback\n*   Changes are transactional. If a step fails, the system must be able to revert to the previous stable state (snapshots/git).\n\n## 4. Performance (HFT Rules)\n\n### 4.1 Zero-Copy Mandate\n*   Data must not be copied between processes unless absolutely necessary. Use `SharedMemory` pointers.\n\n### 4.2 **No LLM in Hot Path**\n*   **LLMs are too slow for real-time control loops.** All decision logic in the hot path (<10ms) must be deterministic code (Rust/Python). LLMs are for dispatch and synthesis only.\n\n### 4.3 Adaptive Rate Limiting\n*   Dynamic adjustment of request rates based on target latency and error rates (`AdaptiveRateLimiter`).\n\n## 5. Capabilities & Self-Perfection\n\n### 5.1 Skill Orchestration\n*   **SkillOrchestrator:** Dynamically loads/unloads skills based on context to save resources.\n*   **ShadowMonitor:** Passive process that observes agent actions and flags deviations from protocol.\n*   **ReportingHook:** Automated post-action reporting to the central log.\n\n### 5.2 Capability Set\n*   **40+ Skills:** Modular tool definitions loaded via `SKILL.md` contexts.\n*   **Vector Memory:** Redis Stack enables semantic recall of past errors and solutions.\n\n## 6. DevOps & CI/CD (DevOps 2.0)\n\nCode quality is enforced before execution.\n\n*   **Pre-Commit Hooks:** Mandatory.\n    *   `shellcheck`: Verify shell scripts.\n    *   `hadolint`: Lint Dockerfiles.\n    *   `black`/`ruff`: Format and lint Python.\n    *   `cargo fmt`: Format Rust.\n*   **Security Scanning:**\n    *   `gitleaks`: Scan for secrets on every commit.\n    *   `dependabot`: Automated dependency updates.\n*   **GitHub Actions:** CI pipeline runs all tests and linters on push.\n\n---\n\n*Verified by SACS-2026 Compliance Subagent.*\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1771181783257}}
{"type":"message","id":"4eae7a9c","parentId":"08d145cc","timestamp":"2026-02-15T18:56:37.675Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Appending the Protocol**\n\nI've successfully read `MASTER_PROTOCOL.md`. My next step is to append section 12, as planned. After that, I will generate the requested list of \"Sacred Core\" files, as per the specifications.\n\n\n**Outlining the Execution**\n\nI'm now fully committed to the action plan. Section 12 is ready for insertion into `MASTER_PROTOCOL.md`. The \"Sacred Core\" file list generation is next; I anticipate a smooth transition to that phase after the append operation.\n\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"write_1771181797670_207","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"# MASTER PROTOCOL (SACS-2026)\n\n**Version:** 3.0.0\n**Status:** ACTIVE\n**Enforcement:** MANDATORY\n\n---\n\n## 1. Core Philosophy (SACS-2026)\n\nThe System Architecture for Cognitive Synthesis (SACS-2026) governs all operations. We prioritize precision, speed, and safety above all else.\n\n*   **Autonomy with Oversight:** Agents operate autonomously but must report status and errors transparently.\n*   **Zero Ambiguity:** Specs must be written before code. Documentation is not an afterthought; it is the blueprint.\n*   **Speed is Safety:** In high-frequency environments, latency causes drift. Minimize latency to maintain control.\n*   **Self-Correction:** The system must identify, contain, and correct faults without human intervention whenever possible.\n\n## 2. Architecture\n\nWe employ a **Polyglot Hybrid Architecture** designed for maximum throughput and safety.\n\n### 2.1 Polyglot Stack\n*   **Rust (Core):** Used for high-performance compute, safety-critical logic, and memory management via PyO3 bindings.\n*   **Python (Glue):** Orchestrates high-level logic, agentic reasoning, and API integrations.\n*   **Shell (Ops):** Standard interface for system interactions.\n\n### 2.2 Memory & Communication\n*   **SharedMemory (HFT 3.0):** Used for the hot path (<0.01ms latency). Zero-copy IPC replaces Redis for critical signaling.\n*   **Redis Stack:** Used for **Agentic Memory** (vectorized logs, semantic search) and state persistence (cold/warm path).\n*   **Orjson:** Mandatory JSON serializer for microsecond-level parsing.\n\n### 2.3 Fleet Status\n*   **Active Nodes:** 730, 570\n*   **Configuration:** Centralized via `docs/ACTIVE_CONTEXT.json`.\n\n## 3. Safety Protocols\n\n### 3.1 The OODA Loop\nEvery task MUST follow the **Observe-Orient-Decide-Act** cycle.\n1.  **Observe:** Gather raw data (logs, state, user input).\n2.  **Orient:** Analyze context against SACS-2026 rules.\n3.  **Decide:** Formulate a plan (write spec/docs).\n4.  **Act:** Execute the change (atomic commit).\n\n### 3.2 Terminal Watchdog\n*   **Strict Oversight:** Agents must actively read `stdout` and `stderr`.\n*   **Zero Ignorance:** Never assume a command succeeded. Verify exit codes and output streams.\n*   **Halt on Error:** If a critical error is detected in `stderr`, the agent must pause and enter a recovery state.\n\n### 3.3 Atomic Rollback\n*   Changes are transactional. If a step fails, the system must be able to revert to the previous stable state (snapshots/git).\n\n## 4. Performance (HFT Rules)\n\n### 4.1 Zero-Copy Mandate\n*   Data must not be copied between processes unless absolutely necessary. Use `SharedMemory` pointers.\n\n### 4.2 **No LLM in Hot Path**\n*   **LLMs are too slow for real-time control loops.** All decision logic in the hot path (<10ms) must be deterministic code (Rust/Python). LLMs are for dispatch and synthesis only.\n\n### 4.3 Adaptive Rate Limiting\n*   Dynamic adjustment of request rates based on target latency and error rates (`AdaptiveRateLimiter`).\n\n## 5. Capabilities & Self-Perfection\n\n### 5.1 Skill Orchestration\n*   **SkillOrchestrator:** Dynamically loads/unloads skills based on context to save resources.\n*   **ShadowMonitor:** Passive process that observes agent actions and flags deviations from protocol.\n*   **ReportingHook:** Automated post-action reporting to the central log.\n\n### 5.2 Capability Set\n*   **40+ Skills:** Modular tool definitions loaded via `SKILL.md` contexts.\n*   **Vector Memory:** Redis Stack enables semantic recall of past errors and solutions.\n\n## 6. DevOps & CI/CD (DevOps 2.0)\n\nCode quality is enforced before execution.\n\n*   **Pre-Commit Hooks:** Mandatory.\n    *   `shellcheck`: Verify shell scripts.\n    *   `hadolint`: Lint Dockerfiles.\n    *   `black`/`ruff`: Format and lint Python.\n    *   `cargo fmt`: Format Rust.\n*   **Security Scanning:**\n    *   `gitleaks`: Scan for secrets on every commit.\n    *   `dependabot`: Automated dependency updates.\n*   **GitHub Actions:** CI pipeline runs all tests and linters on push.\n\n## 12. Domain Management (System vs App)\n\n### 12.1 Definitions\n*   **SYSTEM DOMAIN:** `openclaw.json`, `MASTER_PROTOCOL.md`, `ACTIVE_CONTEXT.json`, `specs/PRD_TEMPLATE.md`, `skills/`.\n*   **APP DOMAIN:** `src/`, `tests/`, `requirements.txt`, `Dockerfile`, `docker-compose.yml`.\n\n### 12.2 Gatekeeper Rule\n\"Classify intent before action. Never mix domains in one commit.\"\n\n### 12.3 Triggers\n*   **\"System Upgrade\"**: Changes affecting the SYSTEM DOMAIN.\n*   **\"Bot Update\"**: Changes affecting the APP DOMAIN.\n\n---\n\n*Verified by SACS-2026 Compliance Subagent.*\n","file_path":"MASTER_PROTOCOL.md"},"thoughtSignature":""}],"api":"google-vertex","provider":"google-vertex","model":"gemini-3-pro-preview","usage":{"input":5842,"output":1328,"cacheRead":4896,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":7170,"cost":{"input":0.011684,"output":0.015936,"cacheRead":0.0009792000000000002,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.028599199999999998}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1771181783260}}
